{
  "Blood plasma makes up approximately what percentage of total blood volume?": "",
  "30%": "",
  "45%": "",
  "55%": "",
  "70%": "",
  "Blood is approximately 55% plasma (the liquid component) and 45% formed elements (red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets), with RBCs making up the vast majority of the formed elements.": "",
  "Hemoglobin's primary function is to:": "",
  "Fight infection": "",
  "Transport oxygen and some carbon dioxide": "",
  "Produce hormones": "",
  "Initiate blood clotting": "",
  "Each hemoglobin molecule can bind up to four oxygen molecules, making red blood cells highly efficient at transporting oxygen from the lungs to tissues and carrying some CO2 back to the lungs.": "",
  "Red blood cells (RBCs) are produced in the:": "",
  "Spleen": "",
  "Red bone marrow": "",
  "Liver": "",
  "Lymph nodes": "",
  "Erythropoiesis (RBC production) occurs in the red bone marrow, which is the primary site of hematopoiesis in adults, found mainly in flat bones like the sternum, pelvis, and vertebrae.": "",
  "Mature RBCs lack a nucleus so that they can:": "",
  "Better resist infection": "",
  "Live longer in circulation": "",
  "Carry more hemoglobin, maximizing oxygen transport": "",
  "Divide more rapidly when needed": "",
  "By ejecting their nucleus and most organelles during maturation, RBCs create more internal space for hemoglobin molecules, maximizing their oxygen-carrying capacity but limiting their lifespan to about 120 days.": "",
  "The most abundant type of white blood cell is the:": "",
  "Monocyte": "",
  "Neutrophil": "",
  "Lymphocyte": "",
  "Eosinophil": "",
  "Neutrophils account for 60-70% of all white blood cells and are the first responders to bacterial infections, where they engulf and destroy pathogens through phagocytosis.": "",
  "Platelets function primarily in:": "",
  "Nutrient transport to tissues": "",
  "Oxygen transport": "",
  "Hemostasis (blood clotting)": "",
  "Immune defense against viruses": "",
  "Platelets (thrombocytes) are cell fragments that adhere to damaged blood vessel walls, form a platelet plug, and release chemicals that initiate the coagulation cascade leading to a stable fibrin clot.": "",
  "Erythropoietin (EPO) is released by the kidneys in response to:": "",
  "High blood oxygen levels": "",
  "Low blood oxygen levels (hypoxia)": "",
  "High platelet count": "",
  "Elevated white blood cell count": "",
  "When the kidneys detect low oxygen levels in the blood, they release erythropoietin, a hormone that stimulates the red bone marrow to increase production of red blood cells, thereby improving oxygen-carrying capacity.": "",
  "Lymphocytes include:": "",
  "T cells, B cells, and natural killer (NK) cells": "",
  "Only T cells": "",
  "Only eosinophils and basophils": "",
  "Only neutrophils and monocytes": "",
  "Lymphocytes are the key cells of adaptive immunity and include T cells (cell-mediated immunity), B cells (antibody production), and natural killer cells (innate destruction of virus-infected and tumor cells).": "",
  "The universal donor blood type is:": "",
  "O-": "",
  "AB+": "",
  "A+": "",
  "B-": "",
  "Type O- blood has no A, B, or Rh antigens on the RBC surface, so it can be transfused to patients of any blood type without triggering an immune reaction, making it invaluable in emergency situations.": "",
  "Blood type is determined by:": "",
  "The number of platelets in the blood": "",
  "Plasma protein concentrations": "",
  "Antigens on the surface of red blood cells": "",
  "The type of white blood cells present": "",
  "Blood type is determined by the presence or absence of specific antigens (A, B, and Rh/D) on the surface of red blood cells, governed by the ABO and Rh blood group systems.": "",
  "What is hematocrit?": "",
  "The concentration of plasma proteins": "",
  "The number of white blood cells per liter of blood": "",
  "The percentage of blood volume occupied by red blood cells": "",
  "The total number of platelets in a blood sample": "",
  "Hematocrit (packed cell volume) measures the proportion of blood volume made up of RBCs, typically ranging from 38-50% in healthy adults, and is used to help diagnose conditions like anemia or polycythemia.": "",
  "What is anemia?": "",
  "A normal variation in blood composition": "",
  "An excess of white blood cells in the blood": "",
  "A decrease in red blood cells or hemoglobin, reducing the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity": "",
  "An excess of platelets causing excessive clotting": "",
  "Anemia is a condition in which the blood has a reduced ability to carry oxygen due to fewer RBCs or less hemoglobin, leading to symptoms such as fatigue, pallor, shortness of breath, and weakness.": "",
  "What is leukemia?": "",
  "A platelet disorder causing excessive bleeding": "",
  "A disorder of red blood cell production": "",
  "A deficiency of plasma proteins": "",
  "A cancer of white blood cells involving abnormal, uncontrolled proliferation of leukocytes": "",
  "Leukemia is a group of blood cancers in which the bone marrow produces large numbers of abnormal, dysfunctional white blood cells that crowd out normal blood cells, impairing immune function and blood cell production.": "",
  "What is thrombocytopenia?": "",
  "A low red blood cell count": "",
  "An excess of white blood cells": "",
  "A low platelet count that increases the risk of bleeding": "",
  "An excess of platelets in the blood": "",
  "Thrombocytopenia literally means low (penia) platelet (thrombo) count (cyt), and it impairs the body's ability to form platelet plugs and initiate clotting, increasing the risk of bruising and hemorrhage.": "",
  "What is sickle cell disease?": "",
  "A genetic disorder where abnormal hemoglobin (HbS) causes RBCs to become rigid and sickle-shaped": "",
  "A blood cancer that affects white blood cells": "",
  "An autoimmune disease that destroys plasma proteins": "",
  "A clotting disorder caused by low platelets": "",
  "Sickle cell disease is caused by a mutation in the hemoglobin gene producing HbS, which polymerizes under low oxygen conditions, distorting RBCs into a rigid sickle shape that can block small blood vessels and cause painful crises.": "",
  "What is albumin?": "",
  "A type of white blood cell": "",
  "A clotting factor that forms fibrin mesh": "",
  "A hormone that stimulates RBC production": "",
  "The most abundant plasma protein that maintains osmotic pressure to keep fluid in blood vessels": "",
  "Albumin is the most abundant plasma protein, produced by the liver, and its primary role is maintaining colloid osmotic pressure that prevents excessive fluid loss from capillaries into the tissues.": "",
  "What is fibrinogen?": "",
  "An antibody produced by B cells": "",
  "A red blood cell protein that carries oxygen": "",
  "A plasma protein that is converted to fibrin during blood clotting to form a stabilizing mesh": "",
  "A hormone released by the kidneys": "",
  "Fibrinogen is a soluble plasma protein produced by the liver that is converted into insoluble fibrin strands by the enzyme thrombin during the coagulation cascade, forming a mesh network that stabilizes blood clots.": "",
  "What does 'universal recipient' mean in blood typing?": "",
  "A person with type O- blood who can donate to anyone": "",
  "A person with type AB+ blood who can receive blood from any type because they have all antigens and no ABO antibodies": "",
  "A person with type B- blood who has no antibodies": "",
  "A person with type A+ blood who can receive from all types": "",
  "Individuals with AB+ blood have A, B, and Rh antigens on their RBCs and therefore produce no anti-A, anti-B, or anti-Rh antibodies, allowing them to safely receive blood transfusions from any ABO/Rh type.": "",
  "What is a complete blood count (CBC)?": "",
  "A test that measures blood type only": "",
  "A test that checks only for cancer markers": "",
  "A test that measures only plasma protein levels": "",
  "The most commonly ordered blood test that provides information about RBCs, WBCs, hemoglobin, hematocrit, and platelets": "",
  "A CBC is the most frequently ordered blood test in medicine, providing a comprehensive snapshot of blood cell counts and characteristics that helps diagnose anemia, infections, clotting disorders, and many other conditions.": "",
  "What does 'erythropoiesis' mean?": "",
  "The process of red blood cell production in the bone marrow": "",
  "The destruction of old red blood cells in the spleen": "",
  "The process of platelet formation": "",
  "The process of white blood cell production": "",
  "Erythropoiesis is the process by which new red blood cells are produced in the red bone marrow, stimulated by erythropoietin from the kidneys, requiring iron, vitamin B12, and folic acid for proper hemoglobin synthesis.": "",
  "A patient living at high altitude for several weeks has a blood test showing elevated RBC count and hemoglobin levels. What physiological mechanism explains these findings?": "",
  "High altitude caused plasma volume to increase, concentrating the RBCs": "",
  "The patient's white blood cells converted into red blood cells": "",
  "Lower oxygen at altitude stimulated the kidneys to release more EPO, increasing RBC production": "",
  "The spleen released stored red blood cells": "",
  "At high altitude, lower atmospheric oxygen causes chronic mild hypoxia, which triggers the kidneys to increase erythropoietin release, stimulating the bone marrow to produce more RBCs and raise hemoglobin to improve oxygen delivery.": "",
  "A patient with liver cirrhosis develops swelling in the legs and abdomen. Lab work reveals very low albumin levels. How does low albumin contribute to this edema?": "",
  "Low albumin increases red blood cell production, expanding blood volume": "",
  "Low albumin causes blood to clot more easily, blocking veins": "",
  "Low albumin causes vasoconstriction, pushing fluid into tissues": "",
  "Low albumin reduces colloid osmotic pressure, allowing fluid to leak out of capillaries into tissues": "",
  "Albumin is the main determinant of plasma colloid osmotic pressure, which normally pulls fluid back into capillaries; when albumin is low, this oncotic force decreases and fluid leaks into the interstitial space, causing edema and ascites.": "",
  "A hemophilia patient cuts his finger and bleeds for an extended period despite applying pressure. Lab results show a normal platelet count. Which part of the clotting process is most likely impaired?": "",
  "The coagulation cascade (clotting factor deficiency preventing fibrin formation)": "",
  "Vasoconstriction of the damaged vessel": "",
  "Platelet plug formation": "",
  "Red blood cell production in the bone marrow": "",
  "Hemophilia is a genetic disorder involving deficiency of specific clotting factors (Factor VIII in hemophilia A or Factor IX in hemophilia B); with normal platelets, the initial plug forms but the coagulation cascade cannot produce sufficient fibrin to stabilize the clot.": "",
  "A blood bank technician accidentally transfuses type A blood into a patient with type B blood. What dangerous immune reaction is most likely to occur?": "",
  "The patient's platelets will increase dramatically": "",
  "The patient's white blood cells will be destroyed": "",
  "The transfused blood will simply be absorbed without effect": "",
  "The patient's anti-A antibodies will attack and lyse the transfused RBCs, causing a hemolytic transfusion reaction": "",
  "Type B blood contains anti-A antibodies; when type A donor RBCs (with A antigens) enter the patient, anti-A antibodies bind to them causing agglutination and hemolysis, which can lead to kidney failure, shock, and death.": "",
  "A 4-year-old child is brought to the emergency department with severe bone pain, fever, and jaundice. Blood work reveals sickle-shaped red blood cells. Why do these abnormal cells cause pain and organ damage?": "",
  "Sickled cells release toxins that damage surrounding tissues": "",
  "Sickled cells trigger excessive platelet activation and massive clotting": "",
  "Sickled cells carry too much oxygen, causing tissue damage": "",
  "Rigid sickle-shaped cells block small blood vessels, causing ischemia and tissue infarction": "",
  "In sickle cell disease, deoxygenated HbS polymerizes, distorting RBCs into rigid sickle shapes that cannot pass through narrow capillaries, causing vaso-occlusion that blocks blood flow, leading to severe pain crises and organ ischemia.": "",
  "A cancer patient undergoing chemotherapy develops fatigue, frequent infections, and easy bruising. Blood work shows low RBCs, WBCs, and platelets. What is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "The patient developed an autoimmune reaction destroying only platelets": "",
  "The cancer spread only to the liver, reducing albumin production": "",
  "The chemotherapy caused excessive blood clotting": "",
  "Chemotherapy suppressed the bone marrow, reducing production of all blood cell types (pancytopenia)": "",
  "Chemotherapy targets rapidly dividing cells, which includes bone marrow stem cells; this causes bone marrow suppression leading to pancytopenia (low RBCs causing fatigue, low WBCs causing infection susceptibility, low platelets causing bruising).": "",
  "A new mother's blood is Rh-negative and her newborn is Rh-positive. The physician recommends an RhoGAM injection. What problem does this prevent in future pregnancies?": "",
  "It prevents the mother from producing anti-Rh antibodies that could attack future Rh-positive babies' RBCs": "",
  "It converts the mother's blood type to Rh-positive": "",
  "It prevents the mother from developing ABO antibodies": "",
  "It increases the baby's platelet count": "",
  "RhoGAM contains anti-Rh antibodies that destroy any fetal Rh-positive RBCs that may have entered the mother's blood during delivery, preventing the mother's immune system from being sensitized and producing her own anti-Rh antibodies that could cause hemolytic disease in subsequent Rh-positive pregnancies.": "",
  "A marathon runner has a blood test showing a hematocrit of 58%, well above the normal range. The physician suspects the athlete may be using a banned substance. Which substance most likely caused this abnormally high hematocrit?": "",
  "Synthetic erythropoietin (EPO)": "",
  "Anabolic steroids": "",
  "Insulin": "",
  "Growth hormone": "",
  "Synthetic EPO artificially stimulates the bone marrow to overproduce red blood cells, significantly raising hematocrit, which increases oxygen delivery but also dangerously thickens the blood, raising the risk of clots, stroke, and heart attack.": "",
  "A patient with chronic kidney disease presents with fatigue, pallor, and a hemoglobin of 8 g/dL. The physician explains that the kidneys are the root cause of the anemia. What mechanism links kidney failure to anemia?": "",
  "Kidney failure causes the spleen to sequester all RBCs": "",
  "Damaged kidneys destroy circulating red blood cells": "",
  "Damaged kidneys cannot produce adequate erythropoietin, so the bone marrow does not make enough RBCs": "",
  "Kidney disease causes excessive iron absorption that poisons the bone marrow": "",
  "The kidneys are the primary producers of erythropoietin; when they are damaged by chronic disease, EPO production drops dramatically, so the bone marrow receives insufficient stimulation and cannot maintain adequate RBC production, causing anemia.": "",
  "A nurse is caring for a patient whose blood work reveals a WBC count of 45,000/uL (normal: 4,500-11,000/uL) with many immature blast cells. The physician suspects leukemia. Why do these abnormal WBCs put the patient at risk for both infection and bleeding?": "",
  "The elevated WBCs cause blood to become too thick to flow through capillaries": "",
  "Cancerous WBCs are dysfunctional and crowd out normal WBCs, RBCs, and platelets in the bone marrow": "",
  "The excess WBCs attack the patient's own healthy tissues": "",
  "Blast cells release enzymes that directly dissolve platelets and RBCs": "",
  "In leukemia, malignant blast cells proliferate uncontrollably in the bone marrow, crowding out normal hematopoietic cells; this results in insufficient functional WBCs (increasing infection risk), low RBCs (anemia), and low platelets (bleeding risk).": ""
}